In TypeScript, a type annotation can indicate to the type system that a value has a specific type, but in practice, the value will only have that specific type. However, the type system is still able to infer the type of the value based on its usage and context.

For example, in TypeScript you can write a function that expects an array as an argument and returns an array as a result:
```
function myFunction(array: any[]): any[] {
    // ...
}
```
This function can accept any object that is an array-like value, such as an array or an object with an `length` property. However, in practice, this function will only work with arrays and the compiler will throw an error if it is passed an object that is not an array. The type annotation serves to tell the compiler that it should treat the input as if it were an array, even though it may not actually be an array.

